<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1905-06-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1905-06-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="1079" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1079">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Hutchinson</persName>
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Caracas</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1905-06-22"><hi rend="italic">June 22,
                                1905</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 434.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that during the
                            last two weeks El Constitucional, the government newspaper, has been
                            devoting a large portion of its space every day to publishing the
                            correspondence which passed between this legation and the Venezuelan
                            foreign office this year relative to the asphalt case. So far, no
                            comments have been added to the said correspondence by the editor. The
                            notes in <pb facs="1109" n="989" xml:id="pg_989"/> question have been
                            copied from the yearly report of the minister of foreign relations.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Norman
                            Hutchinson.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>